text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Expansion: Further examples of stereotypical Indian characters%0a:Author: shreya_r%0a:Original: [[Articles.IndianAccentInTVShows|IndianAccentInTVShows]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.Spencer_L|Spencer_L]]%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 20:47%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210504-192837-4310#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 12:28-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210504-192837-4310#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn addition to the examples of The Big Bang Theory and The Simpsons, characters who speak in stereotypical and overexaggerated Indian accents are also seen in the shows Jessie and Phineas and Ferb. In both shows, the Indian characters (Ravi and Baljeet) are portrayed as extremely nerdy overachievers who are constantly picked on, and they speak with the same heavy accent that was described in this article. This further perpetuates the stereotypes that were brought up here of Indians being intellectual but weak/socially awkward. Since both of these shows had audiences that were primarily children, they allowed these stereotypes to be ingrained into kids at a young age, and then those same stereotypes would be reinforced in shows targeted at older audiences such as the ones described in this article. Furthermore, at least in my experience, these kinds of characters were often the only kind of representation South Asians got in media while growing up.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
